  <data name="lblSendEmailTip.Help" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>1. different values can be read from query string as well like ... &lt;br /&gt;
      a. use [QS:UserID:&lt;span color="red"&gt;uid&lt;/span&gt;]  to send email to user ID as picked from query string value "UID". &lt;br /&gt;
      b. use [QS:UserName:&lt;span color="red"&gt;uname&lt;/span&gt;]  to send email to user ID as picked from query string value "UID". &lt;br /&gt;
     c. use [QS:RoleID:&lt;span color="red"&gt;rid&lt;/span&gt;] to send email to all users in role with ID picked from query string value "rid".&lt;br /&gt;
     d. use [QS:RoleName:&lt;span color="red"&gt;rname&lt;/span&gt;] to send email to all users in role with ID picked from query string value "rid".&lt;br /&gt;
     e. use [QS:Email:&lt;span color="red"&gt;emailid&lt;/span&gt;] to send email to the email address specifyed in querystring value "emailid".&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
 NOTE: query string names (shown in red above) are customizable. Replace them with your actual query string names.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	
2. Values can also be inserted like this ...&lt;br /&gt;
     a. [UserName:John] or [UserName:$(someField)] &lt;br /&gt;
     b. [UserID:12] or [UserID:$(someField)] &lt;br /&gt;
     c. [RoleName:Subscribers] or [RoleName:$(someField)] &lt;br /&gt;
     d. [RoleID:12] or [RoleID:$(someField)] &lt;br /&gt;
	
3. What's more you can mix and match these options by the use of comma for eg : [QS:UserID:&lt;span color="red"&gt;uid&lt;/span&gt;], [UserName:John] &lt;br /&gt;</value>
  </data>
